Backend Structure (Key Files)
🔹 /api/models/
userModel.js
→ Handles user-related DB operations (create user, find user, etc.)
timerModel.js
→ Handles timer and session-related queries

🔹 /api/controllers/
(Functions that handle API logic)
Auth Controller
registerUser() → Creates new user (with hashed password)
loginUser() → Verifies credentials and returns JWT token
Timer Controller
createTimer() → Creates a new timer
startTimer() → Starts a session (records start time)
pauseTimer() → Ends session and calculates duration
getTotalTime() → Returns total time for a timer
getTodayTime() → Returns today's usage
getWeeklyTime() → Returns last 7 days usage

🔹 /api/routes/
auth.routes.js → /auth/register, /auth/login
timer.routes.js → All timer-related endpoints

🔹 /db/
migrations/
make_users_table.js → Users table
make_timers_table.js → Timers + sessions schema
index.js → Knex DB connection (singleton pattern)

🔹 Root Files
server.js → Entry point (Express app setup, routes, middleware)
knexfile.js → DB configuration


Timer Logic (Core Feature)
Instead of directly storing time, the system uses sessions:
 Start → stores start_time
 Pause → stores end_time and calculates duration
 Total time → sum of all session durations


API DEMO (Step-by-Step)
1️ Register User
POST /auth/register
{
  "name": "Aum",
  "email": "aum123@test.com",
  "password": "123456"
}


️2 Login
POST /auth/login
{
  "email": "aum123@test.com",
  "password": "123456"
}

➡️ Returns:
{
  "user": {...},
  "token": "JWT_TOKEN"
}


3️ Create Timer
POST /timers
Headers:
Authorization: Bearer <token>

{
  "name": "DSA Study"
}


4️ Start Timer
POST /timers/:id/start
 Creates a session with start time

5 Pause Timer
POST /timers/:id/pause
 Ends session and calculates duration

️6 Get Total Time
GET /timers/:id/total
{
  "total_seconds": 45,
  "formatted": "0h 0m 45s"
}


️7 Daily & Weekly Stats
/timers/:id/today
/timers/:id/weekly


